{
  "texts": [
    "Although graph neural networks containing pooling operations can model complex hierarchies, larger parameters lead to more noise and lower efficiency.",
    "Compared with DiffPool, EigenPool (Ma et al. 2019b) mainly solves the problem of how to retain the structural information of subgraphs merged into a super node during the hierarchical clustering process.",
    "DiffPool uses a simple summation, while EigenPool uses the graph Fourier transform of the signal on the subgraph to represent the joint output of structural information and feature information, but it is very time-consuming.",
    "Since Diff-Pool does not explicitly consider the relationship that the cluster assignment of a given node should depend on the cluster assignments of other nodes, StructPool (Yuan and Ji 2020) converts the learning of soft assignment matrix into a structured prediction problem that utilizes a conditional random field to capture higher-order information among different nodes.",
    "In addition, StructPool (Yuan and Ji 2020) designs Gibbs energy functions to incorporate graph topology information."
  ]
}